Patching

Webster's Dictionary defines patching as "to put into good order something that is injured, damaged, or defective." In cybersecurity terms, patching is the process of mending software. Software developers work hard to ensure safe and secure products, but tight delivery timelines and the use of shared code repositories and frameworks often leave exploitable security flaws in software. Patching helps ensure the security of software by repairing or mitigating these flaws.

The Software Development Life Cycle

Patching is part of the Maintenance phase of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC):

A key takeaway from the SDLC is that flaws are inevitable, and the software development process is both iterative and ongoing. Software is never "done", only released. A key feature of the Secure Software Development Life Cycle (other than simply adding the word "secure" to the existing phases) and its counterpart DevSecOps, is to build security testing into the earlier phases of development (namely, discovery, design, and development). Building security into earlier development phases allows the QA (Quality Assurance) Team to focus on function and usability, and helps ensure fewer vulnerabilities in the released product.

Change Control

The Windows operating system has nearly 50 million lines of code. Microsoft generates monthly updates for Windows on the second Tuesday of every month - a day known as Patch Tuesday. For most Windows 10 and 11 users, Windows checks for updates daily and installs them during "off" hours. As such, Patch Tuesday is not something that individual end-users need to think about. For server administrators, however, patches need to be rolled out more carefully. Though uncommon, a given patch can do more harm than good, rendering a server inoperable. For this reason, system administrators leverage a formal change control process. This process ensures a patch is first tested in a staging environment, then pushed to a limited number of servers, and finally rolled out to the enterprise once a patch is deemed safe. In large enterprises, patching servers can be a full-time effort.

Patch Management

Keeping systems up to date is complex, and in many cases, well-known software bugs remain unpatched for long periods. The overall process for tracking applied and pending patches is known as patch management. For small operations, keeping track of patches applied and pending can be done with PowerShell and a simple spreadsheet. For larger operations, using a dedicated patching solution that supports Windows and Linux is better. Some vendors, like Automox, offer a cloud/agent-based solution. Other vendors, like ManageEngine, offer dedicated in-house patch management servers. Microsoft itself provides Windows Server Update Service (WSUS) as an installable service for a Windows Server. Some antivirus solutions also track if the operating system is out of date. For example, ESET can track and report when systems need patching.

Ideally, patch management will work hand in hand with vulnerability management. Vulnerability Scanners like Nessus, OpenVAS, and Qualys can help determine if the Operating System or any software running on top of the OS is vulnerable. In the reports produced by vulnerability scanners, vulnerabilities are ranked in order of severity so that the most critical patches can be applied first.
